---
title: A Caesar Salad to Rule Them All with Chicken, Romaine, and Ciabatta Croutons
description: The Caesar in Caesar salad takes its name from the restaurateur who is credited with its invention, Caesar Cardini, not Julius. Nevertheless, the combo of crisp lettuce, creamy dressing, toasty croutons, and sharp Parmesan cheese rules just as hard as any Roman emperor. Our version introduces a squeeze of lemon and rosemary-seasoned chicken breasts to give it extra citrus and herb-driven power.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/a-caesar-salad-to-rule-them-all-140ab59d.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/a-caesar-salad-to-rule-them-all-b0bb313e.pdf
cuisine: North America
time required: 25 minutes
author: Michelle Doll Olson
servings: 2
nutrition:
  calories: 520 kcal
  fat: 23 g
  saturated fat: 5 g
  carbohydrates: 31 g
  sugar: 5 g
  protein: 51 g
  fiber: 7 g
  sodium: 550 mg
course: main course
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/a-caesar-salad-to-rule-them-all-58f93531171c58372156c102
---

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Zest @lemon{1}, then cut into halves. Halve @grape tomatoes{4} lengthwise. Cut @romaine lettuce{1} into bite-sized pieces. Cut @ciabatta bread{1} into 1-inch cubes.

Toss ciabatta with a drizzle of @olive oil{2%tbsp} on a #baking sheet{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toast in oven until crisp and golden, ~{5-6%minutes}. Set aside in a #large bowl{}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season @chicken breasts{2} all over with @dried rosemary{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Add to pan and sear until browned, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. Transfer to a #baking sheet{}. (TIP: You can use the sheet from step 2.) Roast in oven until no longer pink in center, ~{5-8%minutes}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together lemon zest, @garlic{}(to taste), half the @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, @mayonnaise{1%tbsp}, and @dijon mustard{1%tsp} (we sent more mayonnaise and mustard). Add a squeeze of lemon and a large drizzle of @olive oil{} and whisk to combine. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and more lemon (to taste).

Add lettuce, tomatoes, and half the dressing to bowl with croutons. Toss to coat veggies. Once chicken is done roasting, let rest a few minutes, then thinly slice.

Divide salad between plates, then top with chicken slices. Sprinkle with remaining Parmesan and drizzle with remaining dressing (if desired).

> The Caesar in Caesar salad takes its name from the restaurateur who is credited
> with its invention, Caesar Cardini, not Julius. Nevertheless, the combo of crisp
> lettuce, creamy dressing, toasty croutons, and sharp Parmesan cheese rules just
> as hard as any Roman emperor. Our version introduces a squeeze of lemon and
> rosemary-seasoned chicken breasts to give it extra citrus and herb-driven power.